excerpt: Unique & immersive art installations with multimedia elements & a mysterious narrative throughout.
detail_description: Meow Wolf Santa Fe's House of Eternal Return is a 22,000 square foot immersive art experience filled with multimedia elements and a mysterious narrative. Housed in a former bowling alley owned by George R.R. Martin, this fantasy world created by 150 artists offers captivating layers of creative chaos and interactivity without the gore of Game of Thrones. It appeals to both children and adults, inviting visitors to solve the sci-fi-esque disappearance of a fictitious family through clues sprinkled throughout the space.
name: Meow Wolf Santa Fe's House of Eternal Return
address: 1352 Rufina Cir, Santa Fe, NM 87507, USA

excerpt: Rotating exhibits of the work of Georgia O'Keeffe include paintings, sculptures & sketches.
detail_description: The Georgia O'Keeffe Museum in Santa Fe, New Mexico is a tribute to the iconic artist known as the 'Mother of American Modernism.' The museum showcases rotating exhibits featuring O'Keeffe's paintings, sculptures, and sketches. Visitors can explore her innovative perspective on landscapes through pieces like From the Plains and Jimson Weed.
name: Georgia O'Keeffe Museum
address: 217 Johnson St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Historic city plaza with benches, a bandstand & ethnic markets, plus festivals & community events.
detail_description: Santa Fe Plaza is a historic city center that reflects traditional Spanish Colonial cities. Resembling destinations in Mexico and Central America, it features ornate historic buildings surrounding a large plaza where people relax and soak in the special atmosphere. Since its establishment in 1610, the plaza has been central to daily life, hosting centuries of festivities, events, and fairs. The New Mexico History Museum serves as an educational resource and local landmark, offering insights into the diverse experiences of New Mexico's people.
name: Santa Fe Plaza
address: 63 Lincoln Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Leafy road & Santa Fe emblem featuring 100+ art galleries, studios & restaurants in adobe houses.
detail_description: Canyon Road in Santa Fe is a picturesque street lined with over 100 art galleries, studios, and restaurants housed in traditional adobe buildings. It's a favorite activity for visitors to stroll along this legendary road, as well as around the downtown Plaza and the up-and-coming Railyard District. The area is known for its vibrant arts community and offers the opportunity to meet artists during Friday evening gallery openings.
name: Canyon Rd
address: Santa Fe, NM, USA

excerpt: Historic site for weddings & events with a notable spiral staircase with a legend behind it.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Santa Fe, New Mexico, the Loretto Chapel Museum is a captivating historic site that draws visitors with its breathtaking Gothic Revival architecture and enchanting lore. Originally constructed in the late 19th century as part of the Loretto Academy for girls, this chapel features the famous 'Miraculous Staircase,' an architectural marvel that appears to defy gravity with its spiral design and absence of visible support.
name: Loretto Chapel Museum
address: 207 Old Santa Fe Trail, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: 80,000-sq-ft homage to global folk art & culture, featuring art & artifacts from over 100 countries.
detail_description: The Museum of International Folk Art is an expansive 80,000-sq-ft space celebrating global folk art and culture. It houses a diverse collection of art and artifacts from over 100 countries, making it the world's largest collection of international folk art. The museum offers a vibrant and eclectic experience with exhibits that engage visitors of all ages.
name: Museum of International Folk Art
address: On Museum Hill, 706 Camino Lejo, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

excerpt: Famed opera house features classic pieces & contemporary works in a woodsy, hilltop setting.
detail_description: The Santa Fe Opera is a renowned opera festival held in a picturesque hilltop setting, offering classic and contemporary performances. The 64th season, running from July 3 to August 29, features 37 shows including world premieres and company premieres. Visitors can enjoy tailgate dinners before the performances. Santa Fe itself is a vibrant city with a rich history, diverse culture, and strong artistic influence.
name: The Santa Fe Opera
address: 301 Opera Dr, Santa Fe, NM 87506, USA

excerpt: Stately 1800s-era cathedral featuring colorful stained-glass windows & plenty of history.
detail_description: Nestled at the end of East San Francisco Street, the Cathedral Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi is a stunning architectural gem that dates back to the late 19th century. Commissioned by Bishop Jean-Baptiste Lamy, this grand cathedral took 15 years to complete and reflects his vision to elevate Santa Fe's religious landscape beyond its traditional adobe roots.
name: The Cathedral Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi
address: 131 Cathedral Pl, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: 17th-c. adobe governor's palace & museum with exhibits tracing state & Native American history.
detail_description: The New Mexico History Museum, located just a short walk from Santa Fe Plaza, is housed in a 17th-century adobe governor's palace. It offers exhibits that trace the history of the state and its Native American inhabitants. The museum also features eight unique shops offering a variety of items such as apparel, furnishings, jewelry, accessories, music, movies, and Native American art.
name: New Mexico History Museum
address: 113 Lincoln Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: The Santa Fe Farmers Market is a popular spot that offers more than just fresh produce. It's located near the Second Street Brewery at the Railyard, where visitors can enjoy local music and delicious food while taking in the vibrant atmosphere. The area also hosts outdoor concerts, movies, festivals, and art fairs throughout the summer and into fall.
name: Santa Fe Farmers Market
address: 1607 Paseo De Peralta, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Expansive museum featuring over 70,000 Native American artifacts along with interactive exhibits.
detail_description: The Museum of Indian Arts & Culture is a vast museum showcasing over 70,000 Native American artifacts and interactive exhibits. It delves into the unique legacy of Native American culture in the Southwest, spanning ancient times to the present day through a diverse collection of items such as centuries-old pottery, silver jewelry, weaving, and painted automobiles. The museum also features a recreation of a trading post and traditional Pueblo kitchen.
name: Museum of Indian Arts & Culture
address: 710 Camino Lejo, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

excerpt: Expansive collection of contemporary regional art & photography housed in an adobe building.
detail_description: The New Mexico Museum of Art, designed by Isaac Hamilton Rapp in 1917, is a stunning example of Pueblo Revival architecture. The museum houses an extensive collection of contemporary regional art and photography in its adobe building. With a 20,000-piece permanent collection that includes works by renowned artists like Georgia O'Keeffe and Ansel Adams, the museum showcases only a fraction at any given time.
name: New Mexico Museum of Art
address: 107 W Palace Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Santa Fe history museum also provides informational exhibits on the development of New Mexico.
detail_description: The Palace of the Governors at New Mexico History Museum is a part of the Santa Fe history museum, offering informative exhibits on the development of New Mexico. The area also features 8 unique shops with a variety of items including apparel, furnishings, jewelry, accessories, music, movies, and Native American art. The plaza where the palace is located was once bordered by government buildings and a Franciscan missionary church built in 1610-1612.
name: Palace of the Governors at New Mexico History Museum
address: 105 W Palace Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Storied adobe church originally built in the 17th century featuring restored paintings & other art.
detail_description: The San Miguel Chapel is a 17th century adobe church located in Santa Fe, New Mexico. It was originally built by Franciscan friars and Tlaxcalan Indians, and features restored paintings and art. The chapel is a moving tribute to the faith of its congregation, which dates back to the early days of American exploration.
name: San Miguel Chapel
address: 401 Old Santa Fe Trail, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Museum & educational center dedicated to Native American contemporary art plus history & culture.
detail_description: The IAIA Museum of Contemporary Native Arts (MoCNA) is a renowned institution dedicated to showcasing contemporary art created by Native American, First Nations, and other Indigenous artists. It houses an impressive collection of over 9,000 artworks including paintings, sculptures, ceramics, textiles, and media arts.
name: IAIA Museum of Contemporary Native Arts (MoCNA)
address: 108 Cathedral Pl, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: 18,000-sq-ft space hosts notable international & contemporary art exhibits, lectures & discussions.
detail_description: SITE Santa Fe is an 18,000-square-foot space that showcases notable international and contemporary art exhibits, as well as hosts lectures and discussions. The museum underwent a year-long renovation to expand and remodel its original beer warehouse structure, resulting in a distinctive new building designed by SHoP Architects.
name: SITE SANTA FE
address: 1606 Paseo De Peralta, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Santa Fe, New Mexico’s capital, sits in the Sangre de Cristo foothills. It’s renowned for its Pueblo-style architecture and as a creative arts hotbed. Founded as a Spanish colony in 1610, it has at its heart the traditional Plaza. The surrounding historic district’s crooked streets wind past adobe landmarks including the Palace of the Governors, now home to the New Mexico History Museum.
detail_description: Santa Fe, the capital of New Mexico, is known for its Pueblo-style architecture and vibrant arts scene. Founded as a Spanish colony in 1610, it boasts a traditional Plaza and historic district with adobe landmarks like the Palace of the Governors. The city offers a blend of Gothic cathedrals, outdoor activities, chile-infused cuisine, and a strong emphasis on the arts. Santa Fe's rich history is celebrated through various festivals.
name: Santa Fe
address: New Mexico, USA

detail_description: Kakawa Chocolate House in Santa Fe is a unique specialty chocolate shop that offers authentic and historic drinking chocolates. Their hot chocolate drinks are small but intensely rich, focusing on traditional Pre-Columbian Mesoamerican Mayan Aztec and 1600's European drinking chocolates. The Marie Antoinette hot chocolate, made with chocolate, almond milk, orange blossom, cinnamon, and vanilla, is highly recommended.
name: Kakawa Chocolate House
address: 1050 Paseo De Peralta, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: Santa Fe Railyard Arts District is a vibrant hub for contemporary art, featuring galleries like David Richard Gallery, TAI Gallery, and Zane Bennett Contemporary. The area also houses Warehouse 21, an experimental performance space for local youths. This urban-renewal project boasts eco-conscious architecture, a 10-acre park with walking trails and picnic tables, and a plaza next to the Rail Runner commuter train tracks.
name: Santa Fe Railyard Arts District
address: 544 S Guadalupe St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Botanical center for tours & plant education set within a piñon-juniper woodland.
detail_description: Santa Fe Botanical Garden is a nature center that offers tours and plant education in a piñon-juniper woodland. Originally established in 1987, it serves as a sanctuary for native and non-native plants in the Santa Fe region. The garden has two campuses: one at Museum Hill and another at the Leonora Curtin Wetland Preserve, spanning 35 acres. Visitors can enjoy the beauty of dry upland, transitional, and riparian plants while strolling through the garden.
name: Santa Fe Botanical Garden
address: 715 Camino Lejo, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

excerpt: Upscale-casual lunch spot for sandwiches, salads & Mexican food, plus a wine list & Sunday brunch.
detail_description: Museum Hill Cafe is an upscale-casual lunch spot that offers a variety of options including sandwiches, salads, Mexican food, and a wine list. The Museum of Indian Arts and Culture on Museum Hill focuses on the unique legacy of Native American culture through artifacts, music, video presentations, and live art demonstrations. With over 70,000 items on display including centuries-old pottery, silver jewelry, weaving, and painted automobiles by native craftspeople.
name: Museum Hill Cafe
address: 710 Camino Lejo, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

detail_description: Liquid Light Glass is a renowned glass studio in Santa Fe, owned by the acclaimed artist Elodie Holmes. Visitors can witness mesmerizing glass-blowing demonstrations and explore unique pieces at the in-house shop. The studio also offers classes for those interested in learning the art of glass blowing and creating their own masterpieces. Additionally, Liquid Light Glass is a favorite among locals and provides an opportunity to experience the elegance of glasswork as light passes through it.
name: Liquid Light Glass
address: 926 Baca St, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

excerpt: Round building featuring a central hall with a stained-glass ceiling, plus sculpture-dotted grounds.
detail_description: The New Mexico State Capitol, also known as the Roundhouse, stands out as the only circular state capitol in the United States. Its unique design is inspired by the Zia Sun Symbol and reflects the state's Native American heritage. The building serves not only as a political landmark but also as an art gallery, showcasing works by local artists that celebrate New Mexico's cultural heritage and contemporary artistic community.
name: New Mexico State Capitol
address: 490 Old Santa Fe Trail, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: The Santa Fe Indian Market, established in 1922, is one of the oldest and most renowned Native American art markets in the United States. This event features over 800 Native American artists from more than 250 federally recognized tribes in the U.S. and Canada, showcasing a diverse range of artwork including jewelry, sculpture, painting, beadwork, and more.
name: Santa Fe Indian Market
address: 121 Sandoval St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Consignment gallery offering locally sourced art, furniture & accessories in a stylish, comfy space.
detail_description: Edition ONE Gallery is a consignment gallery located at the base of the Sangre de Cristo Mountains in Canyon Road, Santa Fe. This picturesque trail showcases the heritage of Santa Fe's famous arts scene with over 100 galleries, artists' studios, boutiques, and furniture stores. The gallery offers locally sourced art, furniture, and accessories in a stylish and comfortable space.
name: Edition ONE Gallery
address: 729 Canyon Rd, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: Embark on a unique journey with the Sky Railway, traveling between Santa Fe and Lamy, New Mexico. Led by George RR Martin, this historic rail promises an extraordinary experience with entertainment, music, delectable food, and drinks. The two vibrant trains offer a range of activities such as dinner parties and cocktails while enjoying live performances.
name: Sky Railway
address: 430 W Manhattan Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Nature sanctuary hosting wildlife, hiking trails, guided bird walks & tours of Randall Davey Home.
detail_description: Randall Davey Audubon Center & Sanctuary in Santa Fe is a nature sanctuary spread across 135 acres at the end of Upper Canyon Road. It offers a variety of activities such as wildlife viewing, hiking trails, guided bird walks, and tours of the historic Randall Davey Home. The center is home to nearly 200 species of birds, including hummingbirds, scrub-jays, and mountain chickadees.
name: Randall Davey Audubon Center & Sanctuary
address: 1800 Upper Canyon Rd, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

excerpt: Scenic 22-mi. network of mountain trails with a variety of terrain for hiking, running & biking.
detail_description: Dale Ball Trails is a 22-mile network of mountain trails in Santa Fe, offering diverse terrain for hiking, running, and biking. Additionally, the Santa Fe National Forest provides over a hundred miles of double-track trails on the Caja del Rio Plateau. These trails offer opportunities to explore ancient lava flows and historical sites like the La Cieneguilla petroglyphs and the Camino Real.
name: Dale Ball Trails
address: Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Sweeping Santa Fe views from a hilltop park reached by a path lined with city history plaques.
detail_description: Cross of the Martyrs Park on a Santa Fe hill is a great sunset viewing spot with commanding views of the city. The site is adjacent to Prince Park, once home to Fort Marcy which was built by the Army in 1846.
name: Cross of the Martyrs
address: 617 Paseo De Peralta, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Large arts district with galleries, performance spaces, a cinema, restaurants & antique shops.
detail_description: Santa Fe Railyard is a vibrant arts district in Santa Fe, offering a variety of attractions for visitors. The neighborhood features galleries, performance spaces, a cinema, restaurants, and antique shops. Anchored by the award-winning Railyard Park and Plaza, this revitalized district hosts family-friendly events like concerts and singalongs. Visitors can explore the Santa Fe Artists Market on Saturdays and the Railyard Artisan Market on Sundays.
name: Santa Fe Railyard
address: 332 Read St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Rotating Native American mixed media exhibits as well as an arts & crafts shop founded in 1937.
detail_description: The Wheelwright Museum of the American Indian stands as a testament to the rich cultural heritage of Native American artists, being New Mexico's oldest independent museum dedicated solely to their art. Established in 1937, its mission is to honor and showcase the living traditions and creative expressions of Indigenous peoples. Visitors can explore an extensive collection that includes both contemporary and historic Native American art, with rotating exhibits featuring works by current artists.
name: Wheelwright Museum of the American Indian
address: 704 Camino Lejo, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

excerpt: Sleek rooms & suites with rustic accents, plus an elegant restaurant, a bar & a sidewalk eatery.
detail_description: This luxurious inn blends artistry and history with a gastronomic journey into the Southwest. A combination of old and new accents create a sophisticated atmosphere, with handcrafted furnishings that bring both traditional and contemporary touches to the rooms. The Rosewood Inn is especially well-known for its epicurean adventures and famed cuisine, infused with flavors of the southwest.
name: Rosewood Inn Of the Anasazi
address: 113 Washington Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Dramatic adobe house & garden with a big collection of art centered on Western & Southwestern works.
detail_description: Nedra Matteucci Galleries is a must-visit for art enthusiasts, boasting an extensive collection of American art from the 19th and 20th centuries. The gallery features works by renowned artists such as the Taos Society of Artists, American West artists, and masters of American Impressionism and Modernism. Visitors can also explore the Gaugy Gallery showcasing a variety of Jean-Claude Gaugy's signature carved wood paintings.
name: Nedra Matteucci Galleries
address: 1075 Paseo De Peralta, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: This 10-acre former railyard offers gardens, an outdoor performance space & a children's play area.
detail_description: Santa Fe Railyard Park, a 10-acre former railyard, is a vibrant hub of art, music, and outdoor activities. It features gardens, an outdoor performance space, and a children's play area. The park hosts various events including the Santa Fe Artists Market on Saturdays and the Railyard Artisan Market on Sundays. This award-winning outdoor space offers a blend of modern art and contemporary music just a short drive from Santa Fe Plaza.
name: Santa Fe Railyard Park
address: 740 Cerrillos Rd, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

excerpt: Small museum featuring devotional & decorative art, furniture & textiles in Spanish colonial style.
detail_description: The Museum of Spanish Colonial Art features a wide range of artwork from the Spanish Colonial period, including furniture and textiles. The museum is located in Santa Fe, New Mexico and celebrates traditional craftsmanship with modern interpretations inspired by Spanish Colonial artistic traditions and history.
name: New Mexico Heritage Arts Museum
address: 750 Camino Lejo, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

excerpt: Upscale hotel with posh, art-filled rooms set in adobe and stone buildings, plus a wine bar & spa.
detail_description: The Inn of The Five Graces is a luxurious hotel located in historic Santa Fe, offering elegant rooms adorned with art and traditional elements. Guests can enjoy the exquisite decor featuring hand-laid mosaics, Moroccan textiles, and authentic kiva fireplaces. The hotel also boasts a five-treatment-room spa described as world-class by visitors. Its convenient location allows for easy access to attractions such as the San Miguel Chapel and the Georgia O'Keeffe Museum.
name: The Inn of The Five Graces
address: 150 E De Vargas St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: One of the oldest buildings in the US, this snug museum features rustic furnishings & a gift shop.
detail_description: The Oldest House Museum is a historic building located in the Barrio de Analco Historic District, showcasing Spanish Pueblo architecture dating back around 350 years. The museum features rustic furnishings and offers a glimpse into 18th century Santa Fe. Additionally, it houses art collections from different phases of Georgia O'Keeffe's life and stunning photographs of her homes in Ghost Ranch and Abiquiu.
name: Oldest House Museum
address: 215 E De Vargas St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: No-frills, diner-style eatery serving regional favorites, breakfast specials & famously hot chile.
detail_description: Tia Sophia's is a beloved, no-frills diner-style eatery located in the historic city of Santa Fe. Since 1974, this family-run restaurant has been serving up classic New Mexican dishes such as enchiladas, green chile stew, and posole. Renowned for their breakfast burritos, Tia Sophia's is credited with being one of the first to feature them on their menu.
name: Tia Sophia's
address: 210 W San Francisco St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: Santa Fe Spirits Downtown Tasting Room, established by Colin Keegan in 2010, is a local favorite known for its Scotch-style whiskey, apple brandy, and Wheelers Gin. The spirits are sourced locally and have won several awards. The Western Dry Gin is made from five locally sourced botanicals. At the tasting room, visitors can enjoy classic cocktails like Manhattan and prickly pear vodka soda or try the apple brandy and elderflower soda.
name: Santa Fe Spirits Downtown Tasting Room
address: 308 Read St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: Second Street Brewery at The Railyard is a popular spot in Santa Fe, offering local music, good food, and a vibrant atmosphere. The brewery hosts outdoor concerts, movies, festivals, and art fairs throughout the summer and into fall. It's located near the Santa Fe Farmers Market and contemporary art galleries like SITE Santa Fe and Zane Bennett.
name: Second Street Brewery at The Railyard
address: 1607 Paseo De Peralta #10, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: Santa Fe Spirits Distillery, established in 2010, is a renowned craft distillery in New Mexico. The distillery offers tours on Thursdays, Fridays, and Saturdays where visitors can learn about the production of their whiskey, vodka, brandy, and gin. Visitors have praised the friendly bartenders and the inviting atmosphere of the space. The tour and tasting experience has been described as informative and enjoyable by many guests.
name: Santa Fe Spirits Distillery
address: 7505 Mallard Way STE I, Santa Fe, NM 87507, USA

detail_description: Whoo's Donuts is a charming bakery located just outside downtown, offering a wide variety of scratch-made pastries using local ingredients. Despite its unassuming appearance, this funky little cafe boasts an array of exciting and original donut flavors alongside American classics like Boston cream and chocolate-glazed. The shop features an ever-changing selection of colorful donuts, including unique recipes such as maple-bacon, cinnamon-sugar, and sweet corn cake.
name: Whoo's Donuts Pizza and Brew
address: 851 Cerrillos Rd B, Santa Fe, NM 87505, USA

detail_description: Located within walking distance, the Plaza is a historic landmark that has been at the heart of the city for over 400 years. It hosts Indian and Spanish markets, concerts, and community events. The lively atmosphere includes tourists exploring museums and shops, food vendors, street musicians, and locals enjoying the vibrant surroundings.
name: Walking Distance to the Plaza
address: 211 Callecita Pl, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: When you're in Santa Fe, don't miss the New Mexico Museum of Art-Vladem Contemporary, a recent addition to the museum. Located just a short distance from SITE Santa Fe, it showcases its inaugural exhibition with pieces by renowned artists such as Larry Bell, Nancy Holt, Yayoi Kusama, and Agnes Martin. This contemporary art space is definitely worth a visit for art enthusiasts.
name: New Mexico Museum of Art-Vladem Contemporary
address: 404 Montezuma Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: Santa Fe Railyard is a vibrant and trendy district in Santa Fe, known for its bustling Farmers Market and the contemporary art exhibitions at SITE Santa Fe. Over the past five years, this area has seen significant development, including the addition of a park. The opening of the Santa Fe Farmers Market Pavilion in 2008 acted as a catalyst for growth, drawing in boutiques, galleries, and dining establishments.
name: Santa Fe Railyard
address: 716 W Manhattan Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

detail_description: Keshi is a unique gift shop that has a strong connection to the Zuni people. This store sells exclusive jewelry, pottery, art, and minerals that are often beautiful and unique designs. The Zuni connection is evident in many of these items which makes this an excellent place to purchase a souvenir for your trip to Santa Fe.
name: KESHi the zuni connection
address: 227 Don Gaspar Ave Unit 1, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Decadent performing arts space in Spanish Renaissance style hosts film screenings & live shows.
detail_description: The Lensic Performing Arts Center is a stunning venue in Spanish Renaissance style that hosts live shows and film screenings. It is part of the vibrant performing arts scene in New Mexico, alongside other major venues like The Outpost Performance Space in Albuquerque and the Santa Fe Opera. The Lensic offers a diverse range of performances, from classical music to flamenco exhibitions, contemporary jazz, theater presentations, films, and lectures.
name: Lensic Performing Arts Center
address: 211 W San Francisco St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Fine-art gallery in a landmark home, selling works in a variety of media by international artists.
detail_description: Nestled at the vibrant intersection of Canyon Road and Garcia Street, Canyon Road Contemporary Art is a must-visit destination for art lovers exploring Santa Fe's renowned gallery district. This fine-art gallery, housed in a historic landmark home, features an impressive array of contemporary works by both emerging and established international artists. Visitors can immerse themselves in a diverse selection of media including pastel, oil, acrylics, mixed media pieces, fused glass creations, and stunning bronze sculptures.
name: Canyon Road Contemporary Art
address: 409 Canyon Rd, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Historic Southwestern-style hotel offering art-filled rooms, plus courtyard dining & rooftop views.
detail_description: La Fonda on the Plaza is a historic gem that embodies the spirit of Santa Fe, making it a must-visit destination for travelers. This charming Southwestern-style hotel boasts art-filled rooms and offers stunning rooftop views, creating an inviting atmosphere for guests. With its rich history as one of the oldest hotels in America and its past as a beloved Harvey House hotel, La Fonda provides a unique glimpse into the region's heritage.
name: La Fonda on the Plaza
address: 100 E San Francisco St, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA

excerpt: Refined space for artisan jewelry, functional objects & sculptural art from international artists.
detail_description: Patina Gallery, located in Santa Fe, New Mexico, is a renowned art institution that has been showcasing the work of American and European artists since its establishment in the late nineties. The gallery offers a refined space for artisan jewelry, functional objects, and sculptural art from international artists. Visitors can expect to find high-end wearable sculptures in precious metals and stones, as well as larger works like sculptures and paintings.
name: Patina Gallery
address: 131 W Palace Ave, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA
